    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - SINGLE SPEED AXLE: SPICER - ASSEMBLE</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>ASSEMBLE</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="assemble" graphiccount="15">
            <title>PINION</title>
            <para>Refer to
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400733">Figure 33</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400733" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400733" filename="../figg14/G1400733.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 33. Pinion Exploded View</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Press inner pinion bearing cone onto the pinion gear (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400734">Figure 34</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400734" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400734" filename="../figg14/G1400734.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 34. Press Inner Pinion Bearing Cone onto Pinion Gear</caption>
                </figure>
                <para></para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Press roller bearing onto pinion gear (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400735">Figure 35</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400735" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400735" filename="../figg14/G1400735.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 35. Press Roller Bearing onto Pinion Gear</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Stake roller bearing in nine places, using a staking tool (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400736">Figure 36</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400736" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400736" filename="../figg14/G1400736.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 36. Stake Roller Bearing in Nine Places</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Make sure all cage bores are free of nicks, dirt, or any contamination.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install inner pinion bearing cup into pinion cage (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400737">Figure 37</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400737" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400737" filename="../figg14/G1400737.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 37. Install Inner Pinion Bearing Cup into Pinion Cage</caption>
                </figure>
                <para></para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install outer pinion bearing cup into pinion cage (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400738">Figure 38</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400738" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400738" filename="../figg14/G1400738.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 38. Install Outer Pinion Bearing Cup into Pinion Cage</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a feeler gauge or shim stock [.0015 in. (.0381 mm) approx.] to ensure bearing cups
                    are completely seated in bearing bores. This is necessary for proper pinion position (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400739">Figure 39</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400739" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400739" filename="../figg14/G1400739.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 39. Make Sure Bearing Cups Are Completely Seated in Bearing Bores</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place selective preload spacer removed during disassembly onto pinion (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400740">Figure 40</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400740" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400740" filename="../figg14/G1400740.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 40. Place Selective Preload Spacer onto Pinion</caption>
                </figure>
                <para></para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place pinion cage onto pinion gear inner bearing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400741">Figure 41</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400741" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400741" filename="../figg14/G1400741.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 41. Place Pinion Cage onto Pinion Gear Inner Bearing</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install outer pinion bearing cone and washer onto pinion (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400742">Figure 42</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400742" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400742" filename="../figg14/G1400742.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 42. Install Outer Pinion Bearing Cone and Washer onto Pinion</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect end yoke seal surface for grooves caused by lip of seal. If grooves can be
                    detected with a fingernail, it should be replaced.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install end yoke onto pinion without seal to allow proper setting of bearing preload.
                    Tighten pinion nut to 900 to 1200 ft-lbs. (1220 to 1627 N&#8226;m) (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1400743">Figure 43</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1400743" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1400743" filename="../figg14/G1400743.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 43. Tighten Pinion Nut</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>W Model requires a spacer on pinion before installing yoke.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Pinion cage should be rotated while tightening pinion nut to seat and align the pinion
                            bearings.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">There are two methods of measuring pinion bearing preload and both are acceptable.
                    Mechanic's preference and available tools determine which method will be used. Both methods measure
                    torque to rotate.
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">To measure preload with the spring scale, clamp the end yoke horizontally in a
                        soft-jawed vise. Attach one end of cord to a bolt hole in the pinion cage, wrap cord around
                        pinion cage and attach the other end of cord to the spring scale. Rotate pinion cage by pulling
                        scale. Read scale during fourth revolution. Scale reading must be between 3 and 9 lbs. (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1400744">Figure 44</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1400744" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1400744" filename="../figg14/G1400744.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 44. Measuring Preload With Spring Scale</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">To measure preload with the inch pound torque wrench, assemble pinion cage into the
                        carrier housing and install two mounting bolts to anchor the unit. Rotate pinion gear with inch
                        pound torque wrench as shown. Torque measurement will be taken during fourth revolution and must
                        be between 10 and 30 in-lbs. (1.1 and 3.4 N&#8226;m) without pinion seal (rear) (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f1400745">Figure 45</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1400745" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="g1400745" filename="../figg14/G1400745.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 45. Measuring Preload With Inch Pound Torque Wrench</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>When preload reading does not fall within allowable limits, bearing load can be increased by
                        using a thinner spacer or decreased by using a thicker spacer.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>.001 inch (.025 mm) change in preload spacer thickness changes scale reading by approximately
                        10 lbs. .001 change in preload spacer will change torque to rotate by approximately 30 in-lbs.
                        (3.4 N&#8226;m). (This is only a guide. Individual carriers may vary slightly.)
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>Refer to
                <hotlnk xrefid="t1400701">Table 1
                    <xref refid="t1400701"/>
                </hotlnk>
                for available spacer thicknesses. Measure the spacer before assembly to assure correct thickness.
            </para>
